ing>0</percentageDistanceLearning><percentageNightEducation>0</percentageNightEducation><sizeOfTutorialGroups xsi:nil='true'></sizeOfTutorialGroups><teachingTypesInCurriculumYear year='1'><teachingTypeInCurriculum><typeOfTeaching>theory</typeOfTeaching><percentage>50</percentage></teachingTypeInCurriculum><teachingTypeInCurriculum><typeOfTeaching>practice</typeOfTeaching><percentage>30</percentage></teachingTypeInCurriculum><teachingTypeInCurriculum><typeOfTeaching>self study</typeOfTeaching><percentage>20</percentage></teachingTypeInCurriculum></teachingTypesInCurriculumYear></programCurriculum><programDescriptions><contentLink><contentSummary xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[This program produces professional specialists in health and culture and in qualitative methodology who are able to work in multidisciplinary contexts in problem-driven research and intervention projects. With the acquired knowledge, research skills and multidisciplinary focus a medical anthropologist holds a central position in the organization. His ability to design and develop relevant research projects and to share this expertise with colleagues strengthens the organization’s functioning.]]></contentSummary><contentType>website</contentType><subject>sustainable strengthening</subject><webLink xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[http://studieadres.nl]]></webLink></contentLink><contentLink><contentSummary xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[Health is a key factor in the socio-economic sustainable development of individuals, their community and populations. There is an increasing awareness that health is impacted by socio-cultural factors. Medical anthropology provides students with knowledge and research skills to study health perceptions and practices critically in their socio-cultural contexts. This program will enable students to gain insights in the circular relationship between poverty and health and how to break out of it.]]></contentSummary><contentType>website</contentType><subject>socio-economic contribution</subject><webLink xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[http://studieadres.nl]]></webLink></contentLink><contentLink><contentSummary xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[Social scientists, physicians and other health care professionals are familiar with the theories and research methods of medical anthropology; can design and conduct research projects in the field of health and culture, and can participate in multidisciplinary teams.]]></contentSummary><contentType>website</contentType><subject>objectives</subject><webLink xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[http://studieadres.nl]]></webLink></contentLink><contentLink><contentSummary xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[Core: (applied) Medical Anthropology; Culture and Infectious Disease; Comparison of Anthropological and Epidemiological Approaches; Research Methods. Optional: Gender; Reproductive Health and Fertility; Culture; Psychology and Psychiatry; Children, Health and Well-Being; Aids in the 21st Century: a Medical Anthropological Perspective.]]></contentSummary><contentType>website</contentType><subject>curriculum</subject><webLink xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[http://studieadres.nl]]></webLink></contentLink><contentLink><contentSummary xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[Lectures, seminars, tutorials, discussion groups, and individual and group assignments. Students choose to focus their education on themes and regions most relevant to their own work.]]></contentSummary><contentType>website</contentType><subject>instruction modes</subject><webLink xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[http://studieadres.nl]]></webLink></contentLink><contentLink><contentSummary xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[Tuition fees are adjusted annually, for up to date information please see www.uva.nl/isp]]></contentSummary><contentType>website</contentType><subject>tuition fee</subject><webLink xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[http://studieadres.nl]]></webLink></contentLink><contentLink><contentSummary xml:lang="nl"></contentSummary><contentType>website</contentType><subject>brochure</subject><webLink xml:lang="nl"><![CDATA[http://amma.socsci.uva.nl/downloads/flyer_08-09_txt.pdf]]></webLink></contentLink><contentLink><contentSummary xml:lang="nl"><![CDATA[Our program is an excellent starting point for PhD trajectories. 25% of our graduates pursuit and academic career both in social sciences as in medical sciences. ]]></contentSummary><contentType>website</contentType><subject>job perspective</subject><webLink xml:lang="nl"><![CDATA[http://studieadres.nl]]></webLink></contentLink><programDescription xml:lang="nl"><![CDATA[The Amsterdam Master in Medical Anthropology (AMMA) is an advanced master's programme. It is part of the Faculty of Social and Behavioural Sciences of the Universiteit van Amsterdam. 

Within its wide field of research many studies are of a reflective nature, leading to new theoretical perspectives, such as the multi-level perspective. The extensive research has resulted in a steady stream of publications. 

The goal of this course is to provide students with the ability to contribute to the solving of priority health problems. This is reached by helping students learn how to formulate research objectives for medical anthropological research, how to develop feasible study designs which apply relevant theories and concepts, and by demonstrating the means by which good research is conducted, and excellent reports are created. 
Successful students will have mastered a basic knowledge of cultural and medical anthropological concepts and theories and familiarised themselves with qualitative anthropological research methods. In short they will be capable of participating in teams which address problems of health and health care.]]></programDescription><programDescription xml:lang="de"><![CDATA[The first trimester focuses on the field of medical anthropology and its specialisations. All students take two core introductional modules in cultural anthropology and medical anthropology and the core module Studying Health and Disease. 

The second trimester gives an indepth view of medical anthropological approaches. All students take the core module Ethnographies of Health and Health Care. In addition, they must choose two of several thematic modules that reflect themes in the research program of the Medical Anthropology Unit. Thematic modules may vary from year to year. The 2009-2010 course offers:

Gender, Reproductive and Sexual Health and Fertility 
Children, Health and Well-being: a cultural perspective 
Aids in the 21st Century: A Medical Anthropological Perspective 
Culture, Psychology and Psychiatry 
Medicine and Human Rights in Cross-Cultural Perespective 
These thematic modules are open for other students as well, and are organised in the AMMA Winterschool. 

